# Modeling Approach {#modeling-approach}

1. Domain modeling  
   1. Domain expert-based  
      This is based on our understanding of the domain, largely informed by CDL Co-founder George Anadiotis. Additional requirements elicited based on existing resources, such as the website or YouTube channel with the talks, etc.

   2. Automatic  
      **(i)** Confirm the design and/or **(ii)** provide suggestions for new types of entities, relationships or attributes based on different Information Extraction approaches, including LLMs. For example, one such approach could find new aspects from the transcripts not covered with the current metamodel, which can then be considered to include them in it. On the other hand, the automatic identification of entities, relationships and attributes for these two categories could confirm the metamodel as it is, without suggesting new aspects to cover.  
        
2. KG Creation  
   1. RDF-based KG  
   2. Property Graph-based KG

**Attributes**

* title  
* date  
* session {Presentation, Masterclass, Panel, Lightning talk}  
* level {Beginner, Intermediate, Advanced}  
* type {Use cases & Application, Innovation & Research}  
* category {Knowledge Graphs, Graph DBs, Graph Analytics / AI / Data Science, Semantic Tech}

* hasSpeaker \-\> Speaker

# Modeling notes {#modeling-notes}

## Vocabularies to consider {#vocabularies-to-consider}

* Conference ontology: [http://www.scholarlydata.org/ontology/doc/](http://www.scholarlydata.org/ontology/doc/)   
  * Originally created for academic conferences, but covers non-academic as well. Elaborate, specific, uses design patterns for temporal relations  
* Schema.org: [https://schema.org/Event](https://schema.org/Event) , [https://schema.org/CreativeWork](https://schema.org/CreativeWork)   
  * Has classes for Events and CreativeWorks, but not specific classes for Speakers / Talks. But does have classes for things such as Podcast  
* Dublin Core: [https://www.dublincore.org/specifications/dublin-core/dcmi-terms/\#section-6](https://www.dublincore.org/specifications/dublin-core/dcmi-terms/#section-6)   
  * Generic metadata  
* DCAT: [https://www.w3.org/TR/vocab-dcat-3/](https://www.w3.org/TR/vocab-dcat-3/)   
  * Catalog metadata

## Talk {#talk-1}

* The Talk transcript is available via a corresponding attribute. Downstream apps could use it (published on the project repository) for different other (Information Extraction) tasks to further enrich the KG.  
* In principle, there could be Talk instances that don't have either a video or a podcast URL. That would be the case of adding a talk that has not yet been given, or has not yet been released  
  * This could be of help also for any validation operations we want to plan for the KG.  
* The attributes for this entity  
  * session: Presentation, Masterclass, Panel, Lightning Talk (enumeration)  
  * level: Beginner, Intermediate, Advanced (enumeration)  
  * type: Use Cases & Application, Innovation & Research (enumeration)  
  * topic: The terms that describe the topic of the talk.

## Speaker {#speaker-1}

Removed the “bio” attribute. However, this information cen be retrieved from the web site as well as the talk’s YouTube version.

## Podcast {#podcast}

Podcast versions of a talk feature the exact same content. It's just the publishing medium (audio-only) and channel that are different.

In case more information gets added to the podcast page, we could consider treating it as an entity. Until then, we will keep the YouTube and Podcast as two attributes of a talk.

## Category {#category}

Categories are in practice typically handled by CMSs in the same way as talk types. Conceptually, however, categories can be used for any type of categorization.

This is the Connected Data standardized vocabulary for Categories:

* Session Type: Presentation, Masterclass, Panel.   
* Level: Beginner, Intermediate, Advanced.   
* Type: Use Cases & Application, Innovation & Research.  
* Topic. Knowledge Graphs, Graph DBs, Graph Analytics / AI / Data Science, Semantic Tech. 

Note that these will be used in the 2024 event. They do not necessarily apply to past events, as they were not used then. To apply retroactively, the following would be needed:

* Have past talks annotated with those categories  
* Retrieve those annotations

## Organization {#organization-1}

We decided to keep most of the organization-related information out of the scope of the metamodel.

## Relationships {#relationships}

Speaker \- gives \-\> Talk  
Speaker \- isAffiliatedWith \-\> Organization  
Talk \- isPartOf \-\> Event  
Talk \- hasTranscript \-\> Document  
Talk \- hasPublicationMedium \-\> PublicationMedium

- PublicationMedium can be of many types: {Video, Podcast, Presentation, etc.}  
- PublicationMedium can be modeled according to Schema.org.

# Metamodel {#metamodel}

This is the metamodel. It is meant to be the central domain reference from which RDF- or LPG-based implementations can be based on. Specific implementations will adapt their modeling accordingly.

# Implementation approaches {#implementation-approaches}

The two main approaches to building a KG include RDF and Property Graphs. As part of the challenge, we provide a sample representation of the metamodel based on these two approaches. This could help those interested to focus on the IE aspects and populate the KG accordingly.
